        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This spectral resolution (10 km/s) is similar to the one achieved in the HI observations and corresponds to the typical intrinsic linewidth of the gas in these environments. This resolution is sufficient to detect the CO 2-1 line in enough channels over the entire field of view, assuming a (pessimistic) uniform distribution of CO 2-1.

In the same spectral window, we will also be able to detect the CN roto-vibrational line, as a bonus potential bonus to the CO 2-1 observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This angular resolution (0.2'') will allow us to resolve the innermost 0.8 kpc of PKS 1718-649 with ~60 pc of resolution and 35 beams over the distribution of the cold molecular gas. We will disentangle the geometry of the central regions, separating the rotating component from the gas with broad redshifted velocities. Only this resolution will allow us to trace the regions closest to this very young AGN, with sufficient detail to understand the interplay between the different the molecular gas and the radio source. 

Assuming that the CO is distributed as the warm H2, we request a largest angular scale of 2.0''.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The requested sensitivity (0.24 mJy) depends from the need of high S/N observations. Only with S/N=10, we are confident to resolve the molecular hydrogen over the entire field of view, and separate the different kinematical components we detected in the HI and in the warm H2. This is not only a detection experiment, but we are interested in the detailed kinematics of the molecular gas.
We used three independent methods from the HI and the H2 data to estimate the mass of the cold molecular gas. The result from all methods is consistent and equal to 3x10^8 M_sun. Following the conversions in Bolatto et al. 2013, we estimate a luminosity of the CO 1-0 = 7.41 Jy km/s. Assuming an abundance of CO 2-1 twice the one of the CO 1-0, we predict a luminosity of CO 2-1 = 14.82 Jy km/s.
If the CO ranges in the same velocities as the warm H2, we expect the integrated CO line to have width ~150 km/s. This gives an expected flux per channel of ~98 mJy. Assuming that we resolve the distribution of molecular gas with at least 35 ALMA beams (0.2''x0.2''), we expect a flux per beam of: 2.7 mJy.
The required sensitivity is of 0.27 mJy/beam follows directly from S/N=10. The continuum emission at 230 GHz is very low: 260 mJy (SEST observations, Tingay et al. 1997).
If the cold molecular gas follows the same behavior as the warm H2, on a single beam we expect to detect it over 20 km/s, which sets the bandwidth used for sensitivity. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
